   = 1997\u20131998\n| team12           = Bobry Bytom\n| years13          = 1998\u20132000\n| team13           = [[Pogo\u0144 Ruda \u015al\u0105ska]]\n| years14          = 2000\n| team14           = [[Panteras de Miranda]]\n| years15          = 2000\u20132001\n| team15           = [[MKS Znicz Basket Pruszk\u00f3w|Hoop Blachy Pruszy\u0144ski Pruszk\u00f3w]]\n| years16          = 2001\u20132002\n| team16           = [[Gaiteros del Zulia]]\n| highlights   =\n* [[Polish Basketball League|PLK]] All-Star Game MVP (2000)\n* 3\u00d7 PLK All-Star (1996, 1999, 2000)\n* [[Liga Profesional de Baloncesto MVP]] (1992)\n* [[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]] champion ([[1984 National Invitation Tournament|1984]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[1983 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|1983]])\n* [[Michigan Mr. Basketball]] (1983)\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1983)\n* First-team [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|''USA Today'' All-American]] (1983)\n| bbr             =\n}}\n'''Antoine Glen Joubert'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spordefteri.com/basketbolcu/281354/antoine-glen-joubert-kimdir/|title=Antoine Glen Joubert Kimdir|language=tr|website=spordefteri.com|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=colima93>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.ucol.mx/hemeroteca/pdfs/071193.pdf|title=James Anderson, el Mejor Jugador en el Cimeba|language=es|newspaper=Diario de Colima|date=November 7, 1993|page=2B, 9B|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> (born February 20, 1965) is an American basketball coach and former professional player. He played [[high school basketball]] at [[Southwestern High School (Michigan)|Southwestern]] in his native city of [[Detroit, Michigan]], where he was ranked as one of the best players of his class, winning the [[Michigan Mr. Basketball]] award and being named a [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] as a senior in 1983. He signed to play for [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] in college, and was a three-year starter. He was selected in the 6th round of the [[1987 NBA draft]] by the [[Detroit Pistons]] but he did not make the team, and went on to have a 15-year career playing professional basketball abroad, winning MVP honors in [[Venezuela]] and having notable stints in [[Mexico]] and [[Poland]]. After retiring from his playing career, Joubert took up coaching, being hired as the [[head coach]] of [[Oakland Community College]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oaklandcc.edu/foundation/board-of-directors.aspx|title=Board of Directors|website=oaklandcc.edu|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nAfter the end of his college career, Joubert was drafted by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the sixth round of the [[1987 NBA draft]] (134th overall).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1987.html|title=1987 NBA Draft|website=[[Basketball-Reference.com]]|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> He joined the team in the summer<ref name=sun>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1989-07-30-8902230640-story.html|title=SUMMER BEFORE A FALL MOST CAMPERS' MOMENTS OF GLORY PASS QUICKLY|author=Winderman, Ira|date=July 30, 1989|newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> and was kept in the roster during training camps until October 1987.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Minicamp survivors given marginal shot at making Pistons|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|author=Brown, Clifton|date=October 8, 1987|page=63}}</ref> He was later waived by the Pistons before the start of the [[1987\u201388 NBA season]].<ref name=sun /> In December 1987, Joubert was drafted in the [[World Basketball League|International Basketball Association]] (later World Basketball League), a league for players {{height|ft=6|in=5}} and under, being selected by the [[Chicago Express]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Darryl Johnson among IBA draft picks|newspaper=[[Lansing State Journal]]|date=December 9, 1987|page=20}}</ref> Joubert then spent a part of the 1987\u201388 season with the [[Tulsa Fast Breakers]] in the [[Continental Basketball Association]] (CBA), but he never played for the team.<ref name=sun /> In the summer of 1988, Joubert played in the [[Summer Pro League]] with the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref name=sun /> He later moved to [[Belgium]], where he spent his first professional season abroad with [[Sunair Oostende]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Antoine-Joubert/Summary/50833 Profile at RealGM.com]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/antoine-joubert-1.html College stats at Sports-Reference.com]\n*[http://english.worldhoopstats.com/stats/plk-pl/2527-antoine-joubert.html Polish league stats at Worldhoopstats.com]\n*[http://www.plkhistory.ugu.pl/index.php?profil=2527&tab=1 Polish league stats at plkhistory.ugu.pl]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joubert, Antoine}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Belgium]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Colombia]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Mexico]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Michigan]]\n[[Category:BC Oostende players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons draft picks]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:MKS Znicz Basket Pruszk\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:Panteras de Miranda players]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Philippine Basketball Association imports]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n\n[[pl:Antoine Joubert]]\n", "text_old": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Antoine Joubert\n| image           = Antoine_Joubert.jpg\n| width           = 125\n| caption         = Joubert in Poland in 1997\n| team            = \n| league          =\n| position        = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 4\n| weight_lb       = 205\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1965|02|20}}\n| birth_place     = [[Detroit, Michigan]]<ref name=caimanes>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-464466|title=UNO A UNO, LOS CAMPEONES DEL BALONCESTO PROFESIONAL DEL 95|newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]|language=es|date=November 16, 1995|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[Southwestern High School (Michigan)|Southwestern]]<br>(Detroit, Michigan)\n| college         = [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] (1983\u20131987)\n| draft_year      = 1987\n| draft_round     = 6\n| draft_pick      = 134\n| draft_team      = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| career_start    = 1987\n| career_end      = 2002\n| years1          = 1988\u20131989\n| team1           = [[Sunair Oostende]]\n| years2          = 1990\u20131991\n| team2           = [[Lechugueros de Le\u00f3n]]\n| years3          = 1992\n| team3           = [[Panteras de Miranda]]\n| years4          = 1992\n| team4           = [[Lechugueros de Le\u00f3n]]\n| years5          = 1993\n| team5          = [[Dorados de Chihuahua (LNBP)|Dorados de Chihuahua]]\n| years6          = 1994\n| team6          = Pueblo Nuevo\n| years7          = 1995\n| team7           = [[Panteras de Miranda]]\n| years8          = 1995\n| team8           = Caimanes de Barranquilla\n| years9          = 1996\n| team9           = [[Stag Pale Pilseners]]\n| years10          = 1996\u20131997\n| team10           = [[Bobry Bytom]]\n| years11          = 1997\n| team11           = [[Gaiteros del Zulia]]\n| years12          = 1997\u20131998\n| team12           = Bobry Bytom\n| years13          = 1998\u20132000\n| team13           = [[Pogo\u0144 Ruda \u015al\u0105ska]]\n| years14          = 2000\n| team14           = [[Panteras de Miranda]]\n| years15          = 2000\u20132001\n| team15           = [[MKS Znicz Basket Pruszk\u00f3w|Hoop Blachy Pruszy\u0144ski Pruszk\u00f3w]]\n| years16          = 2001\u20132002\n| team16           = [[Gaiteros del Zulia]]\n| highlights   =\n* [[Polish Basketball League|PLK]] All-Star Game MVP (2000)\n* 3\u00d7 PLK All-Star (1996, 1999, 2000)\n* [[Liga Profesional de Baloncesto MVP]] (1992)\n* [[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]] champion ([[1984 National Invitation Tournament|1984]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[1983 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|1983]])\n* [[Michigan Mr. Basketball]] (1983)\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1983)\n* First-team [[USA Today All-USA high school basketball team|''USA Today'' All-American]] (1983)\n| bbr             =\n}}\n'''Antoine Glen Joubert'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spordefteri.com/basketbolcu/281354/antoine-glen-joubert-kimdir/|title=Antoine Glen Joubert Kimdir|language=tr|website=spordefteri.com|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=colima93>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.ucol.mx/hemeroteca/pdfs/071193.pdf|title=James Anderson, el Mejor Jugador en el Cimeba|language=es|newspaper=Diario de Colima|date=November 7, 1993|page=2B, 9B|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> (born February 20, 1965) is an American basketball coach and former professional player. He played [[high school basketball]] at [[Southwestern High School (Michigan)|Southwestern]] in his native city of [[Detroit, Michigan]], where he was ranked as one of the best players of his class, winning the [[Michigan Mr. Basketball]] award and being named a [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] as a senior in 1983. He signed to play for [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] in college, and was a three-year starter. He was selected in the 6th round of the [[1987 NBA draft]] by the [[Detroit Pistons]] but he did not make the team, and went on to have a 15-year career playing professional basketball abroad, winning MVP honors in [[Venezuela]] and having notable stints in [[Mexico]] and [[Poland]]. After retiring from his playing career, Joubert took up coaching, being hired as the [[head coach]] of [[Oakland Community College]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oaklandcc.edu/foundation/board-of-directors.aspx|title=Board of Directors|website=oaklandcc.edu|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nAfter the end of his college career, Joubert was drafted by the [[Detroit Pistons]] in the sixth round of the [[1987 NBA draft]] (134th overall).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1987.html|title=1987 NBA Draft|website=[[Basketball-Reference.com]]|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> He joined the team in the summer<ref name=sun>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1989-07-30-8902230640-story.html|title=SUMMER BEFORE A FALL MOST CAMPERS' MOMENTS OF GLORY PASS QUICKLY|author=Winderman, Ira|date=July 30, 1989|newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> and was kept in the roster during training camps until October 1987.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Minicamp survivors given marginal shot at making Pistons|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|author=Brown, Clifton|date=October 8, 1987|page=63}}</ref> He was later waived by the Pistons before the start of the [[1987\u201388 NBA season]].<ref name=sun /> In December 1987, Joubert was drafted in the [[World Basketball League|International Basketball Association]] (later World Basketball League), a league for players {{height|ft=6|in=5}} and under, being selected by the [[Chicago Express]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Darryl Johnson among IBA draft picks|newspaper=[[Lansing State Journal]]|date=December 9, 1987|page=20}}</ref> Joubert then spent a part of the 1987\u201388 season with the [[Tulsa Fast Breakers]] in the [[Continental Basketball Associations]], but he never played for the team.<ref name=sun /> In the summer of 1988, Joubert played in the [[Summer Pro League]] with the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref name=sun /> He later moved to [[Belgium]], where he spent his first professional season abroad with [[Sunair Oostende]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Antoine-Joubert/Summary/50833 Profile at RealGM.com]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/antoine-joubert-1.html College stats at Sports-Reference.com]\n*[http://english.worldhoopstats.com/stats/plk-pl/2527-antoine-joubert.html Polish league stats at Worldhoopstats.com]\n*[http://www.plkhistory.ugu.pl/index.php?profil=2527&tab=1 Polish league stats at plkhistory.ugu.pl]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joubert, Antoine}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Belgium]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Colombia]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Mexico]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Michigan]]\n[[Category:BC Oostende players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons draft picks]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:MKS Znicz Basket Pruszk\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:Panteras de Miranda players]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Philippine Basketball Association imports]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Detroit]]\n\n[[pl:Antoine Joubert]]\n", "name_user": "Triple 8~enwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional career:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoine_Joubert"}
{"title_page": "Super Dark Times", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Super Dark Times\n| image          = File:Super Dark Times poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Kevin Phillips\n| producers      = Edward Parks<br/>Richard Peete<br/>Jett Steiger\n| writers        = Ben Collins<br/>Luke Piotrowski\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]]\n* [[Charlie Tahan]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]\n| cinematography = Eli Born\n| editing        = Ed Yonaitis\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[The Orchard (company)|The Orchard]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|01|29|[[Rotterdam International Film Festival|Rotterdam]]|2017|09|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $33,109<ref>{{Mojo title |id= superdarktimes|title=Super Dark Times}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Super Dark Times''''' is a 2017 American [[independent film|independent]] [[psychological thriller]] [[drama film|drama]] film directed by Kevin Phillips and starring [[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]] and [[Charlie Tahan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Miska|first=Brad|title=[Tribeca Review] \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 is a Teenage Nightmare|date=21 April 2017|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3431491/tribeca-review-super-dark-times-teenage-nightmare/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Philip|title=Super Dark Times|date=5 May 2017|newspaper=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]|url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2017/may/05/super-dark-times-20170505/?f=entertainment-movies|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|title=FANTASIA 2017, DAY 6: \u201cBAD GENIUS,\u201d \u201cSUPER DARK TIMES\u201d|date=20 July 2017|publisher=[[RogerEbert.com]]|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/festivals-and-awards/fantasia-2017-day-6-bad-genius-super-dark-times|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  It is Phillips' directorial debut.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sokol|first=Tony|title=Super Dark Times Trailer Reveals High School Horrors|date=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Den of Geek]]|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/super-dark-times/266769/super-dark-times-trailer-reveals-high-school-horrors|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Oller|first=Jacob|title=''Super Dark Times'' (2017 Tribeca Film Festival Review)|date=21 April 2017|magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/super-dark-times.html|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Greg|title=\u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Trailer: Moment Of Horror Drives Harrowing Teen Drama|date=2 August 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/super-dark-times-trailer-harrowing-teen-drama-the-orchard-1202141021/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Weissberg|first=Jay|title=Rotterdam Film Review: \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019|date=1 February 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/super-dark-times-rotterdam-film-review-1201975932/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> After a traumatic accident, an inseparable pair of teenage boys and best friends lose their innocence from jealousy, violence and paranoia.\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=March 2018}}\nIn 1996, in upstate New York, two teenage best friends, Zach and Josh, rate the girls in a yearbook. They find a common interest in Allison.\n\nAfter school, the duo crosses the path of the universally-disliked Daryl and his eighth-grade friend Charlie. Later that week, the four boys meet up at Josh's house where they look through the possessions of Josh's brother, who is in the marines. They find a bag of marijuana, a pair of [[nunchaku]], and a [[katana]].\n\nAfterwards the boys slash milk cartons with the katana in a nearby forest. The boys notice that Daryl is smoking a joint and has stolen the marijuana. After a tense argument, Daryl hits Josh. The two fight, resulting in Daryl being accidentally stabbed in the throat with the katana. The boys panic and decide to hide both Daryl's body and the katana.\n\nDuring the next two days of school, rumors circulate about Daryl's disappearance. Zach has nightmares and Josh doesn\u2019t attend classes. Zach wants to return to Daryl's burial site and attend Allison's upcoming party with Josh. Josh refuses to do either.\n\nZach goes to Allison's party where he is surprised to see Josh sharing his brother's weed with everyone. Zach, disturbed, leaves. Allison pursues him and they almost kiss, but Zach says he is unable to and leaves.\n\nAnother student, John Whitcomb, is found dead. Rumors speculate that he fell off a bridge. Zach suspects that John's death was not accidental. He returns to Daryl's burial site and finds the katana missing and Darryl\u2019s corpse unearthed and mutilated. He calls Charlie and tells him that he suspects Josh killed John, but Charlie dismisses it.\n\nZach goes to Josh's house and barges into Josh's room, looking for the katana or evidence of the deaths. Zach sees Allison's phone number on Josh's caller ID and Zach frantically runs look for her. Meanwhile, Josh, Allison and Meghan smoke weed at Meghan\u2019s house. Josh unwraps the katana from under a towel to show it to them.\n\nZach arrives at Meghan's house and quietly makes his way up the stairs. He hears muffled screams coming from Meghan's bedroom and opens the door to find Josh has murdered Meghan. Allison is tied and gagged in the corner, wounded but still alive. Josh locks Zach out of the room, but Zach climbs up on the roof and breaks the window to get back inside. Zach is attacked by Josh and attempts to escape, but Josh slashes his shoulder and stabs him in the leg. Zach attempts to fight him off, but Josh begins to strangle him. A neighbor intervenes, separates them, and holds Josh down.\n\nPolice and paramedics arrive at the scene. While the paramedics attend to Zach's wounds, he glances at Josh sitting in the back of a police car.\n\nMonths later, Allison has recovered and returns to school. A camera shot from the back of the classroom reveals the scars she received from the katana: three parallel lines on the back of her neck.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]] as Zach Taylor \n*[[Charlie Tahan]] as Josh Templeton\n*Elizabeth Cappuccino as Allison Bannister\n*[[Max Talisman]] as Daryl Harper\n*[[Sawyer Barth]] as Charlie Barth\n*[[Amy Hargreaves]] as Karen Taylor\n*Adea Lennox as Meghan\n*Ethan Botwick as John Whitcomb\n*Anni Krueger as Mrs. Barron\n*Kortnee Simmons as Eugene\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Neil|title='Super Dark Times': Film Review; Rotterdam 2017|date=2 February 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/super-dark-times-971268|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  It made its North American premiere on April 20, 2017 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=McGovern|first=Joe|title=Watch an exclusive clip from high school thriller ''Super Dark Times''|date=20 April 2017|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/04/20/super-dark-times-exclusive-clip/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that [[The Orchard (company)|The Orchard]] had acquired worldwide distribution rights to the film in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=\u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Stars & Director Kevin Phillips On An Act Of Violence That Changes Everything \u2014 Tribeca Studio|date=22 April 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/super-dark-times-tribeca-film-festival-kevin-phillips-owen-campbell-interview-news-1202073696/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> The film was released in theaters on September 29, 2017, and digitally on October 3, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=McGovern|first=Joe|title=''Super Dark Times'': Check out a tense trailer for the new high school thriller|date=2 August 2017|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/08/02/super-dark-times-trailer/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> It plays on Netflix streaming.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Dark Times|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/263726/super-dark-times-now-streaming-netflix/|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\n{{expand section|date=February 2020}}\nThe film has an 88% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Dark Times|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/super_dark_times/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> and holds a 75 on [[Metacritic]].\n\nDavid Ehrlich of [[IndieWire]] graded the film a B\u2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ehrlich|first=David|title=Review: \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Is An Unnerving Cross Between \u2018Stand By Me\u2019 and \u2018Donnie Darko\u2019 \u2014 Tribeca 2017|date=20 April 2017|work=[[IndieWire]]|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/04/super-dark-times-review-kevin-phillips-tribeca-film-festival-2017-1201807555/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n''Super Dark Times'' won the best feature film award at the 17th [[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Gash|first=Lawrence|title='Super Dark Times' takes top prize at Neuchatel|date=10 July 2017|magazine=[[Screen Daily]]|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/super-dark-times-takes-top-prize-at-neuchatel/5119803.article|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> It was also the winner of Best Sound Design in a Feature Film at the 2017 Music+Sound Awards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masawards.com/winners-2017/|title=2017 Winners|website=Music+Sound Awards|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref> and received a nomination for the [[Saturn Award for Best Independent Film]] at the [[44th Saturn Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|title=\u2018Black Panther,\u2019 \u2018Walking Dead\u2019 Rule Saturn Awards Nominations|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 15, 2018|access-date=March 15, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xwc1azco?url=http://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  At the [[33rd Independent Spirit Awards]], Kevin Phillips was nominated for the [[Someone to Watch Award]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Nyren|first=Erin|title=2018 Independent Spirit Awards: Winners List (Updating Live)|date=3 March 2018|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/spirit-awards-2018-winners-list-1202716594/amp/|accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[I Am Not a Serial Killer]]''\n* ''[[Summer of 84]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5112578}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|super_dark_times}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Super Dark Times\n| image          = File:Super Dark Times poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Kevin Phillips\n| producers      = Edward Parks<br/>Richard Peete<br/>Jett Steiger\n| writers        = Ben Collins<br/>Luke Piotrowski\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]]\n* [[Charlie Tahan]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]\n| cinematography = Eli Born\n| editing        = Ed Yonaitis\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[The Orchard (company)|The Orchard]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|01|29|[[Rotterdam International Film Festival|Rotterdam]]|2017|09|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $33,109<ref>{{Mojo title |id= superdarktimes|title=Super Dark Times}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Super Dark Times''''' is a 2017 American [[independent film|independent]] [[psychological thriller]] [[drama film|drama]] film directed by Kevin Phillips and starring [[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]] and [[Charlie Tahan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Miska|first=Brad|title=[Tribeca Review] \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 is a Teenage Nightmare|date=21 April 2017|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3431491/tribeca-review-super-dark-times-teenage-nightmare/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Philip|title=Super Dark Times|date=5 May 2017|newspaper=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]|url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2017/may/05/super-dark-times-20170505/?f=entertainment-movies|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tallerico|first=Brian|title=FANTASIA 2017, DAY 6: \u201cBAD GENIUS,\u201d \u201cSUPER DARK TIMES\u201d|date=20 July 2017|publisher=[[RogerEbert.com]]|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/festivals-and-awards/fantasia-2017-day-6-bad-genius-super-dark-times|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  It is Phillips' directorial debut.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sokol|first=Tony|title=Super Dark Times Trailer Reveals High School Horrors|date=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Den of Geek]]|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/super-dark-times/266769/super-dark-times-trailer-reveals-high-school-horrors|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Oller|first=Jacob|title=''Super Dark Times'' (2017 Tribeca Film Festival Review)|date=21 April 2017|magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/super-dark-times.html|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Greg|title=\u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Trailer: Moment Of Horror Drives Harrowing Teen Drama|date=2 August 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/super-dark-times-trailer-harrowing-teen-drama-the-orchard-1202141021/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Weissberg|first=Jay|title=Rotterdam Film Review: \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019|date=1 February 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/super-dark-times-rotterdam-film-review-1201975932/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> After a traumatic accident, an inseparable pair of teenage boys and best friends lose their innocence from jealousy, violence and paranoia.\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=March 2018}}\nIn 1996, in upstate New York, two teenage best friends, Zach and Josh, rate the girls in a yearbook. They find a common interest in Allison.\n\nAfter school, the duo crosses the path of the universally-disliked Daryl and his eighth-grade friend Charlie. Later that week, the four boys meet up at Josh's house where they look through the possessions of Josh's brother. They find a bag of marijuana, a pair of [[nunchaku]], and a [[katana]].\n\nAfterwards the boys slash milk cartons with the katana in a nearby forest. The boys notice that Daryl is smoking a joint and has stolen the marijuana. After a tense argument, Daryl hits Josh. The two fight, resulting in Daryl being accidentally stabbed in the throat with the katana. The boys panic and decide to hide both Daryl's body and the katana.\n\nDuring the next two days of school, rumors circulate about Daryl's disappearance. Zach has nightmares and Josh doesn\u2019t attend classes. Zach wants to return to Daryl's burial site and attend Allison's upcoming party with Josh. Josh refuses to do either.\n\nZach goes to Allison's party where he is surprised to see Josh sharing his brother's weed with everyone. Zach, disturbed, leaves. Allison pursues him and they almost kiss, but Zach says he is unable to and leaves.\n\nAnother student, John Whitcomb, is found dead. Rumors speculate that he fell off a bridge. Zach suspects that John's death was not accidental. He returns to Daryl's burial site and finds the katana missing and Darryl\u2019s corpse unearthed and mutilated. He calls Charlie and tells him that he suspects Josh killed John, but Charlie dismisses it.\n\nZach goes to Josh's house, but no one is home. He barges into Josh's room, looking for the katana or evidence of the deaths. Zach sees Allison's phone number on Josh's caller ID and Zach frantically runs look for her. Meanwhile, Josh, Allison and Meghan smoke weed at Meghan\u2019s house. Josh unwraps the katana from under a towel to show it to them.\n\nZach arrives at Meghan's house and quietly makes his way up the stairs. He hears muffled screams coming from Meghan's bedroom and opens the door to find Josh has murdered Meghan. Allison is tied and gagged in the corner, wounded but still alive. Josh locks Zach out of the room, but Zach climbs up on the roof and breaks the window to get back inside. Zach is attacked by Josh and attempts to escape, but Josh slashes his shoulder and stabs him in the leg. Zach attempts to fight him off, but Josh begins to strangle him. A neighbor intervenes, separates them, and holds Josh down.\n\nPolice and paramedics arrive at the scene. While the paramedics attend to Zach's wounds, he glances at Josh sitting in the back of a police car.\n\nMonths later, Allison has recovered and returns to school. A camera shot from the back of the classroom reveals the scars she received from the katana: three parallel lines on the back of her neck.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Owen Campbell (actor)|Owen Campbell]] as Zach Taylor \n*[[Charlie Tahan]] as Josh Templeton\n*Elizabeth Cappuccino as Allison Bannister\n*[[Max Talisman]] as Daryl Harper\n*[[Sawyer Barth]] as Charlie Barth\n*[[Amy Hargreaves]] as Karen Taylor\n*Adea Lennox as Meghan\n*Ethan Botwick as John Whitcomb\n*Anni Krueger as Mrs. Barron\n*Kortnee Simmons as Eugene\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Neil|title='Super Dark Times': Film Review; Rotterdam 2017|date=2 February 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/super-dark-times-971268|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  It made its North American premiere on April 20, 2017 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=McGovern|first=Joe|title=Watch an exclusive clip from high school thriller ''Super Dark Times''|date=20 April 2017|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/04/20/super-dark-times-exclusive-clip/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that [[The Orchard (company)|The Orchard]] had acquired worldwide distribution rights to the film in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=\u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Stars & Director Kevin Phillips On An Act Of Violence That Changes Everything \u2014 Tribeca Studio|date=22 April 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/super-dark-times-tribeca-film-festival-kevin-phillips-owen-campbell-interview-news-1202073696/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> The film was released in theaters on September 29, 2017, and digitally on October 3, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=McGovern|first=Joe|title=''Super Dark Times'': Check out a tense trailer for the new high school thriller|date=2 August 2017|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/08/02/super-dark-times-trailer/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> It plays on Netflix streaming.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Dark Times|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/263726/super-dark-times-now-streaming-netflix/|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\n{{expand section|date=February 2020}}\nThe film has an 88% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Dark Times|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/super_dark_times/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> and holds a 75 on [[Metacritic]].\n\nDavid Ehrlich of [[IndieWire]] graded the film a B\u2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ehrlich|first=David|title=Review: \u2018Super Dark Times\u2019 Is An Unnerving Cross Between \u2018Stand By Me\u2019 and \u2018Donnie Darko\u2019 \u2014 Tribeca 2017|date=20 April 2017|work=[[IndieWire]]|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/04/super-dark-times-review-kevin-phillips-tribeca-film-festival-2017-1201807555/|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n''Super Dark Times'' won the best feature film award at the 17th [[Neuch\u00e2tel International Fantastic Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Gash|first=Lawrence|title='Super Dark Times' takes top prize at Neuchatel|date=10 July 2017|magazine=[[Screen Daily]]|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/super-dark-times-takes-top-prize-at-neuchatel/5119803.article|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> It was also the winner of Best Sound Design in a Feature Film at the 2017 Music+Sound Awards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masawards.com/winners-2017/|title=2017 Winners|website=Music+Sound Awards|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref> and received a nomination for the [[Saturn Award for Best Independent Film]] at the [[44th Saturn Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|title=\u2018Black Panther,\u2019 \u2018Walking Dead\u2019 Rule Saturn Awards Nominations|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 15, 2018|access-date=March 15, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xwc1azco?url=http://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  At the [[33rd Independent Spirit Awards]], Kevin Phillips was nominated for the [[Someone to Watch Award]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Nyren|first=Erin|title=2018 Independent Spirit Awards: Winners List (Updating Live)|date=3 March 2018|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/spirit-awards-2018-winners-list-1202716594/amp/|accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[I Am Not a Serial Killer]]''\n* ''[[Summer of 84]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5112578}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|super_dark_times}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Alexv413", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Dark_Times"}
{"title_page": "List of Valkyria Chronicles episodes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Valkyria Chronicles'' episodes}}\n[[File:Valkyria Chronicles DVD Volume 1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|''Valkyria Chronicles'' DVD cover of volume 1, released in Japan. Welkin Gunther and Alicia Melchiott, the protagonists of the first ''Valkyria Chronicles'', are featured on the cover.]]\n''Valkyria Chronicles'' is an [[anime]] series loosely based on the [[Sega]] video game ''[[Valkyria Chronicles]]''. It began broadcasting on April 4, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allcinema.net/prog/show_c.php?num_c=333392|script-title=ja:\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-04-08|publisher=All Cinema}}</ref> The show is produced by [[Aniplex]]'s [[A-1 Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.dengeki.com/elem/000/000/120/120894/|title=\u300c\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2\u300d\u304c2009\u5e74\u6625\u306bTV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u5316! \u5236\u4f5c\u306fA-1 Pictures!!|accessdate=2008-11-12|date=2008-11-12|publisher=Dengeki Online}}</ref><ref name=\"ANN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-11-12/valkyria-chronicles-game-to-get-tv-anime-next-spring|title=Valkyria Chronicles Game to Get TV Anime Next Spring|accessdate=2008-11-12|date=2008-11-12|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> The series is directed by Yasutaka Yamamoto<ref name=\"MBS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbs.jp/valkyria/|title=Official Valkyria Chronicles MBS Page|accessdate=2009-07-08|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=\"Cast and Staff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/staff/index.html|title=Official Valkyria Chronicles Cast/Staff Page|accessdate=2009-04-19|language=Japanese}}</ref> and written by [[Michiko Yokote]] under the Project Valkyria Group.<ref name=\"MBS\"/><ref name=\"Cast and Staff\"/> ''Valkyria Chronicles'' aired on [[Animax]], [[Tokyo MX]], [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]], [[Chubu-Nippon Broadcasting|CBC]], [[Chiba Television Broadcasting|Chiba TV]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423013346/http://akibanana.com/?q=node%2F1470 |archivedate=April 23, 2009 |url=http://www.akibanana.com/?q=node/1470 |title=Valkyria Chronicles Anime Series Begins in April |date=2009-02-18 |accessdate=2015-11-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Television Kanagawa]], [[Television Hokkaido]], [[Nippon BS Broadcasting|BS11]] and [[TVQ Kyushu Broadcasting]].<ref name=\"TAF\">{{cite web|url=http://akibanana.com/?q=node/1588|title=Chronicles of Valkyria Anime Starts Broadcast Run in April!|date=2009-03-29|accessdate=2009-04-19}}</ref>\n\nSet during the Second Europan War between The Autocratic East Europan Imperial Alliance and Atlantic Federation, the plot focuses on the Gallian Front fought between the Empire and The Principality of Gallia. Welkin Gunther, a college student and son of the First Europan War hero General Belgen Gunther, Isara Gunther, a brilliant Darcsen mechanic and Welkin's foster sister, and Alicia Melchiott, a baker and member of the Bruhl Townwatch, get involved in the war when the Imperials invade Gallia to secure its rich Ragnite deposits. After managing to escape their hometown Bruhl after the Imperials captured it, the three of them join Squad 7 of the Gallian Militia to help free their country from the Empire.\n\nThe theme song, {{nihongo|\"Asu e no Kizuna\"|\u660e\u65e5\u3078\u306e\u30ad\u30ba\u30ca||lit. \"The Bonds that Lead to Tomorrow\"}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/special/movie/090324pv_m.html|title=TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 \u300c\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2\u300d \u30d7\u30ed\u30e2\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-04-08}}</ref> is performed by [[Himeka|Catherine St. Onge]], as winner of the [[Animax Anison Grand Prix]] competition, under her chosen moniker of Himeka; the original score for the anime is composed and conducted by the game's composer [[Hitoshi Sakimoto]].<ref name=\"mainichi3\">{{cite web|url=http://mainichi.jp/enta/mantan/news/20090226mog00m200037000c.html |title=HIMEKA: \u300c\u79c1\u306f\u97f3\u697d\u3068\u7d50\u5a5a\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d \u30ab\u30ca\u30c0\u51fa\u8eab\"\u30a2\u30cb\u30bd\u30f3\u754c\u306e\u9ed2\u8239\"\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u4f1a\u898b |publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]] |date=2009-02-26 |accessdate=2009-03-06 |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301100407/http://mainichi.jp/enta/mantan/news/20090226mog00m200037000c.html |archivedate=2009-03-01 }}</ref><ref name=\"yahoo3\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302033253/http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20090226-00000010-maiall-ent|archivedate=March 2, 2009|url=http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20090226-00000010-maiall-ent|title=<HIMEKA>\u300c\u79c1\u306f\u97f3\u697d\u3068\u7d50\u5a5a\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d \u30ab\u30ca\u30c0\u51fa\u8eab\"\u30a2\u30cb\u30bd\u30f3\u754c\u306e\u9ed2\u8239\"\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u4f1a\u898b|work=Mainichi Shimbun|publisher=[[Yahoo! Japan]]|date=2009-02-26|accessdate=2009-03-06|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name=\"ann-anison\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-02-18/canada-st-onge-to-sing-valkyria-anime-theme-song|title=Canada's St. Onge to Sing Valkyria Anime's Theme Song|publisher=Anime News Network|date=2009-02-18|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animecenter.jp/eng/200904/05154516.php|title=Chronicles of Valkyria Anime Starts Broadcast Run in April!|date=2009-04-05|accessdate=2009-04-19|publisher=[[Tokyo Anime Center]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423053221/http://www.animecenter.jp/eng/200904/05154516.php|archive-date=2009-04-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her CD single has been released on May 27, 2009.<ref name=\"OCD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/dvdcd/cd.html|title=CD Single section, Official Valkryia Chronicles DVD/CD Page|accessdate=2009-07-01|language=Japanese}}</ref> The ending theme, {{nihongo|\"Ano Kaze ni Notte\"|\u30a2\u30ce\u98a8\u30cb\u30ce\u30c3\u30c6}} is sung by the band [[PE'Z|pe'zmoku]] with a CD single released on May 27, 2009; the special version features a cover of Welkin, Alicia and Faldio.<ref name=\"OCD\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinra.net/news/2009/04/02/130205.php|title=pe'zmoku, \u82e6\u96e3\u3092\u4e57\u308a\u8d8a\u3048\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u300c\u30a2\u30ce\u98a8\u30cb\u30ce\u30c3\u30c6\u300d\u304c\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u6c7a\u5b9a|accessdate=2009-04-19|language=Japanese}}</ref> The second theme song, {{nihongo|\"Kanashimi Rensa\"|\u30ab\u30ca\u30b7\u30df\u30ec\u30f3\u30b5}}, is sung by [[Maria (band)|Maria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/news/index.html|title=\u4eca\u9031\u672b\u3088\u308a\u65b0\u30af\u30fc\u30eb\u7a81\u5165\uff01\u65b0OP\u5834\u9762\u30ab\u30c3\u30c8\u516c\u958b\uff01|accessdate=2009-07-06|date=2009-07-02|language=Japanese}}</ref> that starts episode 14.<ref name=\"New\">{{cite web|url=http://theakiba.com/2009/07/05/valkyria-chronicles-new-op-ed-preview/|title=Valkyria Chronicles New OP ED Preview|accessdate=2009-07-07|date=2009-07-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707232729/http://theakiba.com/2009/07/05/valkyria-chronicles-new-op-ed-preview/|archive-date=2009-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> The second ending song, {{nihongo|\"Hitotsu no Negai\"|\u3072\u3068\u3064\u306e\u9858\u3044}}, is sung by Hikari Inoue<ref name=\"New\"/> beginning from episode 14 until episode 25. Episode 26's ending song is \"Brightest Morning\", which is also performed by Inoue. CD singles for Kanashimi Rensa and Hitotsu no Negai were released on August 12, 2009 and August 5, 2009.<ref name=\"New\"/> A ''Valkyria Chronicles'' drama CD was released on July 24, 2009 with another on October 7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/dvdcd/cd_d.html|title=Drama CD, Official Valkyria Chronicles DVD/CD Page|accessdate=2009-07-01|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nNine [[DVD region code|Region 2 DVDs]] of ''Valkyria Chronicles'' were released, with volume 1 released on August 5, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/dvdcd/dvd01.html|script-title=ja:\u300c\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 1\u300d|accessdate=2009-07-01|language=Japanese}}</ref> Volume 2 was released on September 2, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/dvdcd/dvd02.html|script-title=ja:\u300c\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 2\u300d|accessdate=2009-08-21|language=Japanese}}</ref> Volume 3 was released on October 7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valkyria-anime.com/dvdcd/dvd03.html|script-title=ja:\u300c\u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 3\u300d|accessdate=2009-08-21|language=Japanese}}</ref> Volume 4 was released on November 4, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/gp/switch-language/product/B002I8ODBE?language=en_JP|title=Amazon.co.jp - \u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 4 [DVD] DVD\u30fb\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ec\u30a4 - \u5343\u8449\u9032\u6b69, \u4e95\u4e0a\u9ebb\u91cc\u5948, \u5c71\u672c\u9756\u8cb4|work=amazon.co.jp|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> Volume 5 was released on December 12, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B002ORL9DO|title=Amazon.co.jp - \u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 5 [DVD] DVD\u30fb\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ec\u30a4 - \u5343\u8449\u9032\u6b69, \u4e95\u4e0a\u9ebb\u91cc\u5948, \u5c71\u672c\u9756\u8cb4|work=amazon.co.jp|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> Volume 6 was released January 13, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B002OUQKZI|title=Amazon.co.jp - \u6226\u5834\u306e\u30f4\u30a1\u30eb\u30ad\u30e5\u30ea\u30a2 6 [DVD] DVD\u30fb\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ec\u30a4 - \u5343\u8449\u9032\u6b69, \u4e95\u4e0a\